ExtraaLearn Project

Context

The EdTech industry has been surging in the past decade immensely, and according to a forecast, the Online Education market would be worth $286.62bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 10.26% from 2018 to 2023. The modern era of online education has enforced a lot in its growth and expansion beyond any limit. Due to having many dominant features like ease of information sharing, personalized learning experience, transparency of assessment, etc, it is now preferable to traditional education.

In the present scenario due to the Covid-19, the online education sector has witnessed rapid growth and is attracting a lot of new customers. Due to this rapid growth, many new companies have emerged in this industry. With the availability and ease of use of digital marketing resources, companies can reach out to a wider audience with their offerings. The customers who show interest in these offerings are termed as leads. There are various sources of obtaining leads for Edtech companies, like

  • The customer interacts with the marketing front on social media or other online platforms.
  • The customer browses the website/app and downloads the brochure
  • The customer connects through emails for more information.

The company then nurtures these leads and tries to convert them to paid customers. For this, the representative from the organization connects with the lead on call or through email to share further details.

Objective

ExtraaLearn is an initial stage startup that offers programs on cutting-edge technologies to students and professionals to help them upskill/reskill. With a large number of leads being generated on a regular basis, one of the issues faced by ExtraaLearn is to identify which of the leads are more likely to convert so that they can allocate resources accordingly. You, as a data scientist at ExtraaLearn, have been provided the leads data to:

  • Analyze and build an ML model to help identify which leads are more likely to convert to paid customers,
  • Find the factors driving the lead conversion process
  • Create a profile of the leads which are likely to convert

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of leads and their interaction details with ExtraaLearn. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: ID of the lead

  • age: Age of the lead

  • current_occupation: Current occupation of the lead. Values include 'Professional','Unemployed',and 'Student'

  • first_interaction: How did the lead first interacted with ExtraaLearn. Values include 'Website', 'Mobile App'

  • profile_completed: What percentage of profile has been filled by the lead on the website/mobile app. Values include Low - (0-50%), Medium - (50-75%), High (75-100%)

  • website_visits: How many times has a lead visited the website

  • time_spent_on_website: Total time spent on the website

  • page_views_per_visit: Average number of pages on the website viewed during the visits.

  • last_activity: Last interaction between the lead and ExtraaLearn.

    • Email Activity: Seeking for details about program through email, Representative shared information with lead like brochure of program , etc
    • Phone Activity: Had a Phone Conversation with representative, Had conversation over SMS with representative, etc
    • Website Activity: Interacted on live chat with representative, Updated profile on website, etc

  • print_media_type1: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Newspaper.

  • print_media_type2: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Magazine.

  • digital_media: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn on the digital platforms.

  • educational_channels: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn in the education channels like online forums, discussion threads, educational websites, etc.

  • referral: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn through reference.

  • status: Flag indicating whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not.

# Define a function for later use during the EDA
def print_value_counts(df, column, desc):
  """
    Prints the value counts for a specified column in a DataFrame (percentage and counts).

    Prints the percentage of the total sample for each unique value in the specified column.

    Parameters: df (DataFrame): The DataFrame containing the column.
                column (str): The name of the column for which to print value counts.
                desc (str): A description used for to make the output meaningful.
  """

  for i in df[column].unique():
    print(f"{desc}: {i}")
    #print the percentage of converted leads by age group
    print(df.loc[df[column] == i, "status"].value_counts(normalize = True))
    print(df.loc[df[column] == i, "status"].value_counts())
    print('\n')
    print("-" * 50)
    print()

  column_percentages = df.groupby(column).size() / len(df) * 100
  print(f"Percentage of the sample: {column_percentages}")

# Function to plot stacked bar plots
# look at the effect of two independent variables on the dependent variable
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
  # get the number of unique values for predictor
  count = data[predictor].nunique()
  sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
  tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(by=sorter, ascending=False)
  print(tab1)

  # Normalize the data to see percentages or proportions
  tab2 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize='index').sort_values(by=sorter, ascending=False)
  print(tab2)

  tab2.plot(kind = 'bar', stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
  # move the legend off the visual
  plt.legend(title=target, loc='best', bbox_to_anchor=(1.0, 1.0))
  plt.show()

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions

  1. Leads will have different expectations from the outcome of the course and the current occupation may play a key role in getting them to participate in the program. Find out how current occupation affects lead status.
  2. The company's first impression on the customer must have an impact. Do the first channels of interaction have an impact on the lead status?
  3. The company uses multiple modes to interact with prospects. Which way of interaction works best?
  4. The company gets leads from various channels such as print media, digital media, referrals, etc. Which of these channels have the highest lead conversion rate?
  5. People browsing the website or mobile application are generally required to create a profile by sharing their personal data before they can access additional information.Does having more details about a prospect increase the chances of conversion?

# look at the percentage of leads converted to customers by age group.
for age_group in range(20, int(data['age'].max()), 10):
    # Filter the data for the age group
    total_in_age_group = len(data[(data['age'] >= age_group) & (data['age'] < age_group + 10)])

    # Filter data for the current age group and status 1 (converted to customers)
    filtered_data = data[(data['age'] >= age_group) & (data['age'] < age_group + 10) & (data['status'] == 1)]

    # Calculate percentage for the current age group by comparing all leads for the age group with converted leads
    percentage = (len(filtered_data) / total_in_age_group) * 100 if total_in_age_group else 0
    print(f'There are {total_in_age_group} leads between the age of {age_group} and {age_group + 9} with status 1')
    print(f"Percentage of leads between {age_group} and {age_group + 9} with status 1: {percentage:.2f}%")
    print("-" * 50)
    print()

num_duplicates = data.duplicated().sum()
if num_duplicates > 0:
  # print how many duplicate rows there are in the dataset
  print(f"There are {num_duplicates} duplicated rows.")
  print("-" * 50)
  print()

  # print the duplicated rows
  # Group by all columns and count occurrences to get an idea how many duplicates for each row there are
  duplication_counts = data.groupby(data.columns.tolist()).size().reset_index(name='duplication_count')

  # Filter to show only rows that are duplicated (duplication_count > 1)
  duplicated_rows_with_counts = duplication_counts[duplication_counts['duplication_count'] > 1]

  # Print the results
  print(duplicated_rows_with_counts)

  # Remove duplicate rows, but keep the first occurance
  data = data.drop_duplicates(keep='first')

# From the boxplots above...
# there are outliers to be dealt with
'''
  'website_visits'
  'page_views_per_visit'
'''

# Define a function to remove the bottom 10% of the data (outliers are on the high side)
def remove_outliers(df, column):

  q1 = df[column].quantile(0.10)
  q3 = df[column].quantile(0.90)
  iqr = q3 - q1
  lower_bound = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
  upper_bound = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
  # only include the leads that are in the lower 90% for the feature,
  # unless the outlier is a converted customer
  df_filtered = df[(df[column] <= upper_bound) | (df['status'] == 1)]
  return df_filtered

# remove entire row for outliers of type website_visit and page_views_per_visit
data = remove_outliers(data, 'website_visits')
data = remove_outliers(data, 'page_views_per_visit')

In[231]:
# try engineering one useful feature and then drop all the lead columns
# put all the leads into one lead_type column based on the types of lead
'''
  Values:
    No lead type = 0
    lead type is either newspaper, magazine, digital, or educational = 1
    More than one lead type (excluding referral)= 3
    lead type is referral = 3
    More than one lead type (including referral) = 4
'''

# Create the 'lead_type' column based on the conditions
# Initialize with default value 0 (none of the lead columns are 'Yes' - majority)
data['lead_type'] = 0

# If any of the other lead columns are 'Yes', assign 1 to lead_type
data.loc[(data[lead_cols[:-1]] == 1).any(axis=1), 'lead_type'] = 1

# If more than one lead type is 'Yes' (excluding referral), assign 2 to lead_type
data.loc[(data[lead_cols].sum(axis=1) > 1) & (data['referral_lead'] == 0), 'lead_type'] = 2

# If 'referral_lead' is 'Yes', assign 1 to lead_type
data.loc[data['referral_lead'] == 1, 'lead_type'] = 3

# If referral and another lead type are 'Yes', assign 4 to lead_type
data.loc[(data[lead_cols].sum(axis=1) > 1) & (data['referral_lead'] == 1), 'lead_type'] = 4

# drop the lead_cols
data.drop(lead_cols, axis=1, inplace=True)

# Function to compute different metrics to check classification performance

def model_performance_metrics(model, predictors, target):
    '''
      Print the classification report and return the scores
    '''

    # Predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)
    recall = recall_score(target, pred,average = 'binary')
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average = 'binary')
    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, average='binary')

    # Creating a dataframe of metrics to report out
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame({"Precision":  precision,
                            "Recall": recall,
                            "Accuracy":  acc,
                            "F1_Score": f1}, index = [0],)

    return df_perf
In[239]:
# Function to print the classification report and get confusion matrix in a proper format

def model_confusion_matrix(actual, predicted):
  '''
    Function to check classification model performance
    Print the classification report and confusion matrix
    Return metric score
  '''

  cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)

  plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5))

  sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True,  fmt = '.2f', xticklabels = ['Not Converted', 'Converted'], yticklabels = ['Not Converted', 'Converted'])

  plt.ylabel('Actual')
  plt.xlabel('Predicted')
  plt.show()

# Decision Tree Classifier - perform cross-validation and hyperparameter tuning

# Use the class_weight hyperparameter to handle the unbalanced data for the status field
# class_weight = {0: 0.3, 1: 0.7} counters unbalanced data because status = 1 occurs only about 30% of the time
dt_tuned_classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = 1,
                                             class_weight = {0: 0.3, 1: 0.7})

# Grid of parameters to choose from (3840 combinations)
parameters = {'max_depth': [None, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10],
              'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
              'min_samples_leaf': [4, 6, 8, 10],
              'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2', 2, 4],
              'min_samples_split': [2, 4, 6, 8, 10],
              'max_leaf_nodes': [5, 10, 15, 20]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations - f1_score
# the f1_Score will give me a combination of precision and recall
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(f1_score, pos_label = 1)

# Run the grid search for hyperparameter tuning
# use cross-validation with 5 folds - TRAIN 5 MODELS - use the average
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(dt_tuned_classifier, parameters, scoring = scorer, cv = 5)

# Use the oversampled data set
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Set the classifier to the best combination of parameters
dt_tuned_classifier = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data
dt_tuned_classifier.fit(x_train, y_train)

Actionable Insights and Recommendations

Key Takeaways:

  • The tuned random forest classifier was a good performer and performed even better when the max_depth of the tree was reduced to 10. Conclude with the key takeaways in form of important features identified. - Provide Recommendations such that the business can take action upon them.

  • The Accuracy for the classifier is nearly 86%, which means we are only misclassifying 14% of the leads.

  • The recall for the classifier is roughly 76%. This means we are incorrectly classifying 24% of the leads that convert to customers as leads that will not convert to customers. I was able to get very high recall scores (97%), but always at the expense of precision. This will be something to talk to ExtraaLearn about. Maybe they will want to prioritize recall, which will require a change to the algorithm.

***Recommendations:**

  • Website activity is important: if they are looking to invest money in development of new content, it should be on their website and not the mobile app. Getting leads on the website and engaged is crucial.
  • All advertisement should lead potential customers to the website.
  • The first interaction (first impression) is important. The website should be the primary target that ExtraaLearn pushes potential customers toward.
  • Find ways to get the customers entering their profile data. Leads that get to the website and create a comprehensive profile will convert to customers at a high rate.
  • ExtraaLearn should focus on professionals and unemployed leads. Students are of little interest, as they do not convert to customers often.
  • The age of their leads is a good indicator of converting to customers. ExtraaLearn can confidently target older leads (50's) and make their advertisements age specific along with their website.
  • Email interaction seems to be prefered by customers over phone interaction.
  • The mobile app has not been successful in bringing in many new customers and should be analized for effectiveness. This may be due to the older leads, so ExtraaLearn may have to adapt.
